Part 2

The corridor had become unusually silent. Government hospitals never truly become silent; they merely change the reason for their noise. 

The casualty nurse came out of the ICU doors holding a small glass vial containing a blood sample. "O positive?" she shouted toward the laboratory attendant, who was sorting requisition slips at the corner table.

He looked up, checking a ledger. "First testing," he called back.

"Don't assume," she said, almost throwing the vial into his hand. "Run." The attendant disappeared down the stairs, his slippers squeaking on the wet stone.

The old NGO volunteer slowly walked towards the emergency room door. "Can I see him?" she asked.

"No," the nurse said, without looking up. She had probably answered the same question a hundred times that morning. The girl quietly stepped back, holding the strap of her canvas bag.

A little boy, hardly eight years old, came running through the main glass door. He was holding a small, three-tiered steel tiffin box. "Didi," he called out, his face red from the heat.

She smiled for the first time since the accident. "You came alone?"

He nodded proudly, pointing toward the gate. "Cycle."

She opened the lid of the tiffin box. Inside were four dry rotis, a small portion of yellow potato curry, and a small piece of dark palm jaggery wrapped in a scrap of old newspaper.

"Baba didn't eat today," the boy said, his hand resting on the corner of the reception counter. "He said he would eat after telling us the crow story."

She looked through the glass pane of the ICU door. "He will tell the story," she said.

The boy believed her immediately. Children have a strange, direct faith; it is only adults who ask for proof.

The nurse came out again, looking at the papers in her hand. "Attendant."

The girl hurried forward. "Yes?"

"Blood loss is more than expected," the nurse said, her voice dropping. "We may need blood."

"I'll give," the girl said. The answer came so quickly that the nurse didn't even raise her head from the chart.

"Good," she said, writing a name. "Come."

The girl followed her down the narrow corridor to the blood bank. It was a small, poorly lit room with a single old ceiling fan that clicked as it turned, stirring the heavy, hot air.

The room had three green plastic chairs, a rusty iron weighing scale, and a calendar on the wall showing last year's calendar. The technician sat behind a desk, looking sleepy as he adjusted a fresh needle.

"Name?" he asked. She answered.

He wrote it down. "Age?" She answered. "Weight?" She answered.

Then, he paused, his pen hovering over the last row. "Any illness?"

Silence.

The technician looked up. "Madam?"

She looked down at the grey floor tiles. "...Yes."

"What?"

Another silence followed, heavy and long. The nurse became impatient, checking the watch on her wrist. "Madam... we don't have time."

The girl slowly raised her eyes, her face quiet. "I... have AIDS."

The room became completely still. The clicking of the fan suddenly sounded much louder in the silence. 

The technician quietly set his pen down on the desk, his hand retracting from the form. The nurse stared at her. For a second, there was irritation in the nurse's eyes, then guilt, and then a slow embarrassment.

She spoke much more softly this time, her voice dry. "I'm sorry."

The girl smiled, her hands folded in her lap. "It is alright. I asked to give blood. I never said I could."

Nobody spoke. After a few seconds, the technician quietly took the half-filled form, folded it, and tore it in two without saying anything.

The girl stood up. "I'm sorry," she whispered.

The nurse looked away toward the medicine cupboard. "No... you don't have to be."

When the girl walked back out, two ward boys who had been standing near the blood bank entrance had already heard the conversation. One whispered to another, his head turning to watch her.

Within a minute, half the corridor knew. The same people who had stood shoulder to shoulder with her in the crowd now unknowingly made a little space around her. 

It wasn't much. Just an inch of empty space on either side. Just enough to hurt.

She noticed. She stepped slightly to the left, making the space a little wider, the way you adjust a chair for a guest who is already seated. Nobody saw her do it. If they had, they might have thought she was simply moving. She was.

She noticed it, but she pretended not to. She walked back to her plastic chair, sat down, and looked toward the ICU door. Nothing else mattered.

The little boy came running to her chair again. "Didi, can I see Baba once?"

"No," she said.

"When?"

"When he wakes up," she promised.

The boy accepted the answer. Children trust promises; it is only adults who remember the excuses.

The laboratory attendant came running back up the stairs, holding a slip of paper. "O positive," he shouted.

The nurse looked around the crowded corridor. "Relative?"

Nobody answered. 

She shouted louder, her voice echoing. "Any relative of Budha Baba?"

Silence.

The NGO girl stood up, her hand holding her bag. "He has no family."

The nurse almost lost her patience, looking at the requisition slip. "What kind of life is this..." she muttered, her hand on her hip.

Before she could finish the sentence, someone from the back of the crowd stepped forward. "I'll give," a voice said.

Everyone turned. It was the flower seller, his hands still carrying the green threads he used to tie marigold garlands.

Immediately, the retired postman came beside him, his khaki bag resting on his hip. "My blood is also O positive. Take mine."

The security guard near the desk raised his hand. "Mine too."

The college student looked confused, shifting his backpack. "I don't know my blood group... but test mine. If it matches, take it."

The auto driver spoke from behind the pillar. "If needed, take mine first. The accident happened near my auto stand. I brought him."

The nurse looked at them. One after another, the people in the corridor kept walking forward, lining up near the desk. 

A tea seller, a tailor, a bus conductor, and the old woman who sold jasmine flowers outside the temple—all joined the line. Within two minutes, there were fifteen people standing in a quiet queue.

Nobody asked: *Who is he?* 

Nobody asked: *What relation do we have?* 

Nobody asked: *Will someone pay for the blood?* 

They simply stood there.

The laboratory technician came out of the back room, carrying a tray of syringes. He stopped, counted the queue of fifteen people, and looked at the nurse. 

Then he smiled, a real smile. "For the first time," he said, "I have more donors than blood bags."

The nurse looked through the glass pane of the door toward the unconscious old man. She whispered, almost to herself: "Who are you, Baba?"

The answer came from somewhere behind the crowd. It was a familiar voice—quiet, respectful, and dry.

"Ask anyone outside. They'll tell you. But don't ask Baba himself. He never tells."

The crowd slowly turned. An old tea vendor had just arrived, his shirt dusty from the roadside stove. He removed his slippers before standing near the ICU door. 

He folded his hands, closed his eyes, and smiled, as though he had just come to visit someone from his own family.

[End of Part 2]
